# .template-manifest — ownership map for the LLZ template scaffold.
#
# Classifies every file an instance carries so an update tool can apply template
# changes WITHOUT clobbering instance-local edits. It is the contract behind
# "pull template updates cleanly":
#   - `llz ci template-manifest` validates this file covers the whole scaffold
#     (CI fails if a scaffold file matches no rule), and classifies a given path
#     on demand.
#   - a future template-sync tool reads it to decide, per file, whether to
#     overwrite / 3-way-merge / skip.
#
# FORMAT: one rule per line — `<class>  <glob>`. Globs are POSIX shell globs
# rooted at the instance repo root (= instance-template/ inside the template
# repo); `**` matches across directories. Blank lines and `#` comments ignored.
# PRECEDENCE: last matching rule wins — put specific overrides AFTER general rules.
#
# CLASSES:
#   managed  Template owns it outright. An update OVERWRITES it. Do NOT hand-edit
#            it in an instance — your change will be lost on the next sync (and
#            belongs upstream in the template anyway).
#   merge    Template owns the logic, but the file carries a few fork-local tokens
#            (your GitHub org/registry, your state bucket). An update 3-way-merges
#            it; expect conflicts ONLY on those token lines, which you re-resolve.
#   owned    The instance owns it (per-deployment config, generated files, secrets,
#            provider locks). An update NEVER touches it.

# ── managed: pure template logic — overwritten on update ─────────────────────
managed  .template-manifest
# Declares paths `llz upgrade` removes after a copier update (copier never deletes
# files the template drops). Template-owned — overwritten on update.
managed  .template-removals
# Digests of the vendored .github/ surface, written by `llz ci workflows-fresh
# --write`. `llz lint` recomputes them offline so a hand-edited (and therefore
# doomed — see `managed`) workflow body fails CI instead of being silently
# overwritten on the next upgrade. Ships with the files it covers, so it is
# template-owned too.
managed  .template-workflows.lock
# Composite actions are VENDORED into every instance (.github/actions/) so the
# reusable llz-* workflow bodies reference them locally (./.github/actions/<name>)
# with no cross-repo fetch — this is what lets an instance run self-contained on an
# air-gapped GitHub Enterprise. Token-free template logic — overwritten on update so
# fixes propagate.
managed  .github/actions/**
# Instance-local checks live in `llz` itself (llz lint / fmt / validate — tofu fmt
# / tflint / actionlint / gitleaks / checkov), not in the instance, so fixes ship
# with the binary. Only the lint CONFIGS stay here — the tools read them. Template
# owns them — overwritten on update so fixes propagate. The pre-commit hook is
# installed per-clone by `llz hooks` (copier.yml runs it on copy), not delivered.
managed  .tflintrc.hcl
managed  .checkov.yaml
managed  .gitleaks.toml
# .gitignore is safety-critical — it keeps the .llz/ credential cache (Linode/GitHub
# PATs, OBJ keys) and Terraform state out of git. Template-owned so the ignore can't
# silently drift out of an instance; extend local ignores via .git/info/exclude.
managed  .gitignore
# LandingZone spec starting templates (landingzone.yaml.example +
# environments/<env>.yaml.example) — template-provided reference, overwritten on
# update. The active landingzone.yaml + environments/<env>.yaml an instance authors
# are `owned`, below (the .yaml and .yaml.example globs are disjoint).
managed  landingzone.yaml.example
managed  environments/*.yaml.example
owned    landingzone.yaml
owned    environments/*.yaml
# Operational tooling is NOT classified here: it's template-INTERNAL and not
# delivered to instances (unlike .github/actions above, which IS vendored now).
# The former instance-scripts/ were assimilated into the llz CLI, which is baked
# into the ci-terraform CI image (the ci-terraform target of dockerfiles/Dockerfile)
# the reusable `llz-*` workflows run in, so an instance carries no scripts/ for
# this manifest to own.
# Operator docs (runbooks/playbooks/architecture/…) are delivered from the repo-
# root docs/ tree by copier.yml `_tasks` (OUTSIDE the scaffold), so they refresh
# on update — overwrite-managed, never hand-edited in an instance.
managed  docs/**
# Instance landing page — links to the local docs/ tree + the common `llz` flow.
# Template-owned (like the other READMEs) so improvements reach instances on update;
# instance-specific notes belong in docs/ or a separate file, not here.
managed  README.md
# Instance-root agent/contributor conventions (spec-is-truth, manifest ownership,
# no-secrets/no-AI-attribution). Template-owned like the other AGENTS.md files so
# rule updates reach instances; terraform-iac-bootstrap/AGENTS.md overrides in-tree.
managed  AGENTS.md
managed  terraform-iac-bootstrap/AGENTS.md
# Gitignores the per-env <env>.tfvars that `llz render` regenerates (the spec is
# the source of truth) — see the file's header. Template-owned.
managed  terraform-iac-bootstrap/.gitignore
# (The cluster-bootstrap/ rules that sat here matched nothing: there is no
# cluster-bootstrap Terraform root any more — installing apl-core is
# `llz ci bootstrap-cluster`, run from the bootstrap-openbao job.)
managed  apl-values/README.md
# The apl-core values BASE. Template-managed — `llz render` renders every env's
# values.yaml from it and writes only the per-env overlay (owned, below). The heavy
# platform manifests (the always-on manifest base, the per-component trees, and the
# secret-store bootstrap tree) live at platform-apl/ (repo root, OUTSIDE the
# scaffold) and are fetched as pinned kustomize remote refs, so they are no longer
# part of the instance and carry no manifest entry. The operator's OWN manifests are
# not under apl-values/ at all — see kubernetes-custom/** below.
managed  apl-values/values.yaml

# ── merge: template logic carrying fork-local tokens (org / registry / bucket) ─
# Workflow CALLER STUBS (terraform.yml, promote.yml, …) carry instance-local pins
# (instance_repo, template-ref, the renovate depName) + any dispatch defaults you
# tune — 2-9 copier substitutions each — so they genuinely need the 3-way merge.
merge    .github/workflows/**
# The vendored llz-*.yml REUSABLE BODIES are a different animal: every one of them
# is token-free (verified: no copier substitution appears in any llz-*.yml), so an
# instance's copy is byte-identical to the render unless it was hand-edited. Ship them
# `managed` so `llz upgrade` overwrites them from a clean render of the target
# version instead of 3-way-merging ~4k lines of YAML per bump. That is what makes a
# large body change (e.g. moving maintainer rationale out of the vendored YAML) land
# as a clean overwrite rather than a merge that can strand conflict markers in
# 1000-line workflow files — the gsap-apl v0.0.24 failure mode. Operators must not
# hand-edit these; `llz ci workflows-fresh` fails CI when one drifts.
# (Last-match-wins, so this MUST stay after the `merge .github/workflows/**` above.)
managed  .github/workflows/llz-*.yml
# GitLab CI flavor: the parallel pipeline files a GitLab instance `include:`s from
# the template — same fork-local include/image refs as the GitHub workflows.
merge    gitlab-ci/**
# Renovate: the packageName/registryUrls you repoint to your fork on adoption.
merge    renovate.json
# Dev Container: devcontainer.json pins the prebuilt toolchain image by the
# upstream template org (<@ upstream_org @>) — repoint it if you build your own.
merge    .devcontainer/**
# TF roots: the `git::` module source host/org you repoint to your fork. The
# ?ref= is the copier llz_version (a pinned vX.Y.Z tag), re-pinned in lockstep by
# `llz upgrade` — NOT Renovate-managed (renovate.json disables the self-reference).
# Backend: template ships the backend block; you fill in bucket/key/endpoint.

# ── owned: per-instance state/config/secrets — never touched by an update ─────
# Provider lockfiles: regenerated per instance by `terraform init`.
owned    terraform-iac-bootstrap/*/.terraform.lock.hcl
# Operator allow-list CIDRs for the control-plane ACL (your IPs).
owned    terraform-iac-bootstrap/cluster/extra-acl-cidrs.txt
# Per-deployment overlays — the thin per-env kustomization + values, generated by
# `llz render`. apl-values/ now holds ONLY the base values.yaml (a file, managed
# above) plus these generated env dirs, so this glob needs no managed re-assertion
# after it: nothing shared sits under apl-values/*/ any more.
owned    apl-values/*/**
# Operator escape hatch for custom Kubernetes resources. The template ships the
# namespaces/ + global/ skeleton once and never touches it again, so an instance's
# own manifests here survive every `copier update`. It sits at the REPO ROOT, not
# under apl-values/: it is not apl-core values, and a dir under apl-values/ would be
# a sibling of the generated env dirs where `llz env add <name>` could clobber it.
# The instance-custom ApplicationSet that syncs it is render-generated into each
# env's overlay. See docs/extending-llz.md.
owned    kubernetes-custom/**
# Generated per-env Terraform inputs (llz env add writes these; not the
# committed *.example). Never present in the template tree itself.
owned    terraform-iac-bootstrap/**/*.auto.tfvars
owned    terraform-iac-bootstrap/**/[a-z]*.tfvars
# Operator escape hatches, never shipped by the template:
#   .llz/commands.yaml      — instance-specific `llz` subcommands (replaces the old
#                             Makefile.local; see docs/extending-llz.md).
#   .githooks/pre-commit.local — extra pre-commit checks, run by `llz precommit`
#                             after the built-in lint gate.
# `copier update` never touches them.
owned    .llz/commands.yaml
owned    .githooks/pre-commit.local
# Template provenance stamp (written by llz env add / llz upgrade / llz ci stamp-template-version).
owned    .template-version
# Copier answer tracker (rendered + maintained by `copier copy`/`copier update`).
owned    .copier-answers.yml
